00:49:02,072 --> 00:49:04,404
It should be taught
in all the history books.

700
00:49:04,574 --> 00:49:07,839
I mean, hung and framed
in the National Gallery or something.

701
00:49:08,011 --> 00:49:10,673
Because this is the instant of creation...

702
00:49:10,847 --> 00:49:14,112
...of one of the greatest fortunes
in the history of the world.

703
00:49:14,284 --> 00:49:19,916
I mean, Bill Gates is the richest guy in the
world because of what started in this room.

704
00:49:20,090 --> 00:49:21,523
You wanna know what else?

705
00:49:21,692 --> 00:49:25,685
It wasn't exactly smoke and mirrors,
but we didn't have anything.

706
00:49:25,862 --> 00:49:29,593
I mean, not a damn thing.

707
00:49:30,100 --> 00:49:32,261
Here we were, this two-bit little outfit...

708
00:49:32,436 --> 00:49:36,395
...telling IBM we had the answer
to their problems.

709
00:49:36,573 --> 00:49:39,337
DOS? The Disk Operating System?

710
00:49:39,509 --> 00:49:43,240
To make all those zillion
IBM computers compute?

711
00:49:43,413 --> 00:49:47,509
We didn't even remotely own
anything like what Bill was selling them.

712
00:49:47,684 --> 00:49:50,016
<i>Nada, zip.</i>

713
00:49:55,058 --> 00:49:57,925
Of course, we don't just
wanna sell it to you outright.

714
00:49:58,095 --> 00:50:00,086
We wanna be able to license it to you.

715
00:50:00,263 --> 00:50:03,596
- You want to retain ownership?
- Right.

716
00:50:04,835 --> 00:50:10,432
Well, the profits are in the computers
themselves, not this software stuff.

717
00:50:13,877 --> 00:50:15,469
No big deal.

718
00:50:16,146 --> 00:50:17,374
Oh, and one other thing.

719
00:50:17,547 --> 00:50:19,708
We have to be able...

720
00:50:19,883 --> 00:50:22,374
...to sell it to other outfits.

721
00:50:24,621 --> 00:50:25,952
But...

722
00:50:26,123 --> 00:50:30,958
...there was just one little problem.

723
00:50:32,262 --> 00:50:35,754
Bill, why did you tell them
we have an operating system?

724
00:50:35,932 --> 00:50:38,560
We don't have a thing to sell them now.
We're dead.

725
00:50:38,735 --> 00:50:42,831
- We're not. You'll give us the miracle, right?
- Oh, yeah, right.

726
00:50:43,006 --> 00:50:46,635
Well, come on. You said you knew a guy
we could buy an operating system from.

727
00:50:46,810 --> 00:50:48,801
I said I sort of know him.

728
00:50:48,979 --> 00:50:52,142
Sort of? You heard me.
Don't tell me "sort of. " I just told IBM.

729
00:50:53,683 --> 00:50:55,583
Sort of.

730
00:51:01,491 --> 00:51:04,153
- Here you go.
- Thanks.

731
00:51:19,609 --> 00:51:23,101
So basically, you're saying
you wanna buy my operating system.

732
00:51:23,280 --> 00:51:24,508
Yeah.

733
00:51:29,486 --> 00:51:30,714
Why?

734
00:51:34,858 --> 00:51:40,797
You know, I don't know. We just think we
might be able to mess with it and resell it.

735
00:51:40,964 --> 00:51:42,192
Who to?

736
00:51:42,365 --> 00:51:45,129
We have a few customers, you know,
we're sort of talking to.

737
00:51:45,302 --> 00:51:47,827
Some of them don't want it known
what we're doing.

738
00:51:48,004 --> 00:51:51,405
So they made us sign
a secrecy agreement.

739
00:51:54,611 --> 00:51:57,409
- And you're offering us...?
- Fifty thousand.

740
00:51:57,581 --> 00:52:00,345
- Dollars?
- Dollars.

741
00:52:07,591 --> 00:52:08,819
You worried?

742
00:52:08,992 --> 00:52:12,052
Oh, no. Only my whole life hangs
in the balance. Me, worried? No.

743
00:52:13,463 --> 00:52:15,328
We got IBM.

744
00:52:15,499 --> 00:52:17,990
IBM. I mean, come to think of it...

745
00:52:18,168 --> 00:52:21,660
...why would IBM wanna make a deal
with a bunch of bozos like us?

746
00:52:21,838 --> 00:52:23,829
Because they're successful, Ballmer.

747
00:52:24,007 --> 00:52:27,602
Success is a menace. It fools smart people
into thinking they can't lose.

748
00:52:39,389 --> 00:52:40,788
So?

749
00:52:44,094 --> 00:52:46,221
So, you mute moron?

750
00:52:58,408 --> 00:53:01,275
<i>Can you hear it? The sound of money?</i>

751
00:53:02,846 --> 00:53:06,304
<i>The roar of money. It was like everywhere
you turned, money poured down. </i>

752
00:53:06,483 --> 00:53:08,417
<i>Millions and more millions. </i>

753
00:53:08,585 --> 00:53:13,045
<i>All because we bought that guy's
operating system for a measly 50,000 bucks. </i>

754
00:53:13,223 --> 00:53:18,718
<i>That fueled a worldwide explosion of wealth
unlike anything in the history of man. </i>

755
00:53:18,895 --> 00:53:21,159
<i>But you know something?</i>

756
00:53:21,331 --> 00:53:26,428
<i>Having money and being cool
are not necessarily the same thing. </i>

757
00:53:26,603 --> 00:53:28,901
- Hi, I'm Bill Gates...
- Hey.

758
00:53:29,839 --> 00:53:31,739
What in the...?

759
00:53:33,343 --> 00:53:34,640
Hi.

760
00:53:35,212 --> 00:53:37,646
You know, you should really watch
where you're going.

761
00:53:38,215 --> 00:53:40,183
You must have really great bandwidth.

762
00:53:40,350 --> 00:53:43,285
- Excuse me?
- What are you doing later?

763
00:53:49,092 --> 00:53:51,083
Who is that jerk?

764
00:53:54,531 --> 00:53:56,260
Way to go, hotshot.

765
00:53:59,703 --> 00:54:02,866
When Paul and I were at Lakeside,
we were in 10th grade together...

766
00:54:03,039 --> 00:54:06,372
...we rigged a computer so we could
get classes with all the best girls.

767
00:54:06,543 --> 00:54:08,477
Obviously, it's been downhill since then.

768
00:54:08,645 --> 00:54:12,274
You should walk around with your bankbook
hanging from a chain on your belt.

769
00:54:12,449 --> 00:54:15,976
Or maybe you ought to stop yelling
in front of your employees.

770
00:54:16,152 --> 00:54:19,178
Girls don't like yelling. They like cool.

771
00:54:19,356 --> 00:54:21,984
Oh, really, Ballmer?
How do you get to be cool?

772
00:54:22,692 --> 00:54:25,661
<i>I don't know. You saw
Saturday Night Fever. Travolta's cool.</i>

773
00:54:54,357 --> 00:55:00,023
I'd like to welcome all of you to the new
headquarters and home of Apple Computers.

774
00:55:00,196 --> 00:55:02,391
<i>All of a sudden, Steve was a huge star. </i>

775
00:55:02,565 --> 00:55:05,329
<i>The kind where people practically
hang on your every word... </i>

776
00:55:05,502 --> 00:55:07,902
<i>... like they're excited
just to be around you. </i>

777
00:55:08,071 --> 00:55:12,007
Thank you very much
for joining us today on this lovely day...

778
00:55:12,175 --> 00:55:14,803
...and helping us stop the gossip rumors
in their tracks.

779
00:55:14,978 --> 00:55:16,843
Without further ado,
the rumors are true.

780
00:55:17,013 --> 00:55:19,504
Ladies and gentlemen,
our new president, John Sculley.

781
00:55:25,555 --> 00:55:29,457
To tell you the truth, I was perfectly happy
to be president of Pepsi-Cola...

782
00:55:29,626 --> 00:55:33,118
...until Steve Jobs came to recruit me
and said:

783
00:55:33,296 --> 00:55:36,094
"Do you wanna sell sugared water
for the rest of your life...

784
00:55:36,266 --> 00:55:37,858
...or do you wanna make history?"

785
00:55:39,369 --> 00:55:41,030
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

786
00:55:41,204 --> 00:55:43,229
- I know.
- Yeah, operator.

787
00:55:43,406 --> 00:55:46,432
- I need information for Oregon.
- Okay, give me a minute.

788
00:55:51,114 --> 00:55:54,311
Steve, I gotta talk. I don't know how
to act in situations like this.

789
00:55:54,484 --> 00:55:57,180
- In a minute.
- I mean, Steve, that stock-offering thing?

790
00:55:57,354 --> 00:55:58,582
A hundred million dollars?

791
00:55:58,755 --> 00:56:00,916
- What do you do with $ 116 million?
- In a minute.

792
00:56:01,091 --> 00:56:05,050
I don't think rich, okay? I know a lot of
people think rich, but I don't think rich.

793
00:56:05,228 --> 00:56:09,255
I mean, maybe you learn it, but, jeez,
$ 100 million. That's a lot of learning to do.

794
00:56:09,432 --> 00:56:12,424
I hardly ever had enough for lunch
before all this.

795
00:56:13,203 --> 00:56:15,603
We should have given stock
to the other guys, Steve.

796
00:56:15,772 --> 00:56:18,434
Like Dan?
Dan's been with us since we started...

797
00:56:18,608 --> 00:56:21,304
...and you didn't set aside
any stock for him.

798
00:56:23,446 --> 00:56:25,107
Steve.

799
00:56:25,915 --> 00:56:28,713
- I'm gonna give Dan some of my stock.
- Yeah, is Arlene there?

800
00:56:28,885 --> 00:56:30,580
We gotta do the right thing.

801
00:56:31,154 --> 00:56:33,418
<i>Arlene? Okay, fine. 
Let's talk about this baby. </i>

802
00:56:33,590 --> 00:56:36,821
Steve, why do you care
what I call the baby?

803
00:56:36,993 --> 00:56:40,053
Because I don't want
the baby named Rainbow.

804
00:56:40,230 --> 00:56:44,257
Or Orisha or Ravi Shankar
or any other name like that.

805
00:56:44,934 --> 00:56:47,368
Steve, not right now, okay?

806
00:56:47,537 --> 00:56:51,200
<i>Well, when the hell is a good time to call?
Because every time I try...</i>

807
00:56:54,043 --> 00:56:55,840
Steve.

808
00:57:44,327 --> 00:57:46,261
- Do you want me to take that?
- Thank you.

809
00:57:46,429 --> 00:57:48,124
You're welcome.

810
00:58:12,388 --> 00:58:13,855
Hi.

811
00:58:14,457 --> 00:58:15,947
Hi.

812
00:58:18,795 --> 00:58:21,764
So I just came by to make sure
everything's okay.

813
00:58:23,132 --> 00:58:25,794
- Everything okay?
- Thank you.

814
00:58:37,714 --> 00:58:39,807
And to...

815
00:58:39,983 --> 00:58:43,248
...make sure that you're not
gonna name it some weird name.

816
00:58:46,890 --> 00:58:49,950
What's wrong with naming her Orisha?

817
00:58:50,894 --> 00:58:52,953
Or Sunshine or Purity?

818
00:58:54,597 --> 00:58:57,088
A kid's got enough problems
in this world...

819
00:58:57,267 --> 00:58:59,292
...not knowing where it belongs.

820
00:58:59,469 --> 00:59:00,993
A name can label a kid.

821
00:59:02,071 --> 00:59:03,629
Make it...

822
00:59:03,806 --> 00:59:06,172
It can make it an outsider.

823
00:59:06,910 --> 00:59:08,434
Not "it. "

824
00:59:08,611 --> 00:59:09,839
Her.

825
00:59:11,080 --> 00:59:12,638
Her.

826
00:59:24,127 --> 00:59:25,685
Lisa.

827
00:59:29,599 --> 00:59:31,260
Okay.

828
00:59:31,734 --> 00:59:33,224
Okay.

829
00:59:36,172 --> 00:59:38,106
She's your daughter too.

830
00:59:40,143 --> 00:59:43,374
Arlene, let's not go through that again.

831
00:59:56,559 --> 00:59:59,551
You don't just live in life.

832
00:59:59,729 --> 01:00:04,393
You change it, you shape it,
you make your mark upon it.

833
01:00:05,068 --> 01:00:07,662
And that's what, get used to the name...

834
01:00:08,371 --> 01:00:11,238
...Lisa is gonna do.

835
01:00:11,407 --> 01:00:12,635
Yeah!

836
01:00:12,809 --> 01:00:16,210
<i>You know, that computer was
the first big new project we had at Apple. </i>

837
01:00:16,379 --> 01:00:20,577
<i>And some people are still wondering
why Steve insisted on that name. </i>

838
01:00:21,618 --> 01:00:23,586
You wanna call a computer Lisa?

839
01:00:24,787 --> 01:00:26,778
Isn't that your baby's...?

840
01:00:26,956 --> 01:00:28,685
I mean...

841
01:00:28,858 --> 01:00:33,591
What's her name? Arlene.
Isn't that Arlene's baby's name?

842
01:00:33,763 --> 01:00:36,493
Other guys here
have daughters named Lisa.

843
01:00:36,666 --> 01:00:41,035
Steve, you got a baby up there
you don't even wanna talk about.

844
01:00:41,904 --> 01:00:46,034
- I mean, it looks sort of...
- Sort of what?

845
01:00:55,318 --> 01:00:59,186
We have to think of ourselves as artists.

846
01:01:00,490 --> 01:01:02,754
It's like Picasso said:

847
01:01:02,925 --> 01:01:06,622
Good artists copy. Great artists steal.

848
01:01:08,765 --> 01:01:11,598
<i>This is who we wanted
to steal from. Xerox. </i>

849
01:01:11,768 --> 01:01:14,293
<i>They were secretly developing
all this amazing stuff... </i>

850
01:01:14,470 --> 01:01:18,338
<i>... like the mouse and the graphics on the
screen instead of just a bunch of numbers. </i>

851
01:01:18,508 --> 01:01:21,341
<i>But when those California engineers
had to go to New York... </i>

852
01:01:21,511 --> 01:01:24,105
<i>... and present all this neat stuff
to the Xerox brass... </i>

853
01:01:24,280 --> 01:01:27,772
<i>... those executives didn't begin
to understand what they were looking at. </i>

854
01:01:27,950 --> 01:01:33,547
<i>Never mind a mouse. It was like someone
dumped a dead rat on the boardroom table. </i>

855
01:01:41,197 --> 01:01:42,994
A mouse.

856
01:01:47,270 --> 01:01:51,331
You want Xerox to consider
something called a mouse?

857
01:01:57,480 --> 01:01:59,812
<i>See, this is where Steve was a genius... </i>

858
01:01:59,982 --> 01:02:03,577
<i>... because he persuaded Xerox
into showing us all this incredible stuff... </i>

859
01:02:03,753 --> 01:02:05,550
<i>... their California guys had developed. </i>

860
01:02:05,722 --> 01:02:08,350
<i>I tell you, it was making their people
absolutely nuts. </i>

861
01:02:09,759 --> 01:02:11,488
Oh, God.

862
01:02:15,098 --> 01:02:17,032
Let's go.

863
01:02:18,167 --> 01:02:20,761
<i>You know, I felt like
one of the Mongol hordes... </i>

864
01:02:20,937 --> 01:02:24,668
<i>... coming to loot and plunder
a bunch of defenseless villagers. </i>

865
01:02:26,676 --> 01:02:29,440
No, no. This is insane.

866
01:02:29,612 --> 01:02:31,739
We'd just be handing him everything.

867
01:02:31,914 --> 01:02:37,079
We created the mouse and all the rest of it,
and now these idiots in New York...

868
01:02:37,253 --> 01:02:39,278
...want to show it all to Steve Jobs.

869
01:02:39,455 --> 01:02:40,820
I won't do it.

870
01:02:40,990 --> 01:02:43,982
Hi. I'm Steve Jobs.

871
01:02:46,729 --> 01:02:50,130
I need you to answer some other questions
about the stuff you've invented.

872
01:02:50,299 --> 01:02:52,290
The graphic interface?

873
01:02:54,771 --> 01:02:56,568
It's not going to hurt.

874
01:02:57,073 --> 01:02:58,506
That's what you think.

875
01:03:00,576 --> 01:03:03,067
- What do you want to know?
- How does it...?

876
01:03:03,246 --> 01:03:05,942
What is your base length?
Is it integer, or is it compound?

877
01:03:06,115 --> 01:03:08,640
Does your operating system
convert to executable codes?

878
01:03:08,818 --> 01:03:12,254
- I got it. I got it, Steve-O. I got it, Steve-O.
- What is the middle...?

879
01:03:17,426 --> 01:03:20,020
It's pretty neat, right?

880
01:03:20,196 --> 01:03:22,790
Click, you're there.

881
01:03:23,132 --> 01:03:25,191
Click, you're somewhere else.

882
01:03:25,368 --> 01:03:29,429
This graphic interface stuff was like
a miracle back then, and we got it.

883
01:03:29,605 --> 01:03:33,769
Steve got it, from Xerox, who just
turned it all over for us to fool with.

884
01:03:33,943 --> 01:03:37,401
Like rich people giving junky old stuff
to the Salvation Army...

885
01:03:37,580 --> 01:03:40,879
...only the junk turns out
to be a Rembrandt.

886
01:03:41,050 --> 01:03:44,611
About $ 100 billion head start
on everyone else.

887
01:03:44,787 --> 01:03:48,416
Apple was making tons of money.
It was great.

888
01:03:48,591 --> 01:03:53,290
And of course, I sort of lost my mind.
I mean, it was all fun and games.

889
01:03:53,462 --> 01:03:56,056
I started buying really expensive toys.

890
01:03:57,934 --> 01:04:00,300
<i>It was me with my own plane. </i>

891
01:04:00,469 --> 01:04:03,996
<i>Only problem was, maybe I wasn't
as good a pilot as I thought I was. </i>

892
01:04:04,173 --> 01:04:07,404
<i>I mean, it's one thing
when computers crash, but planes?</i>

893
01:04:07,577 --> 01:04:08,805
<i>You don't want to know. </i>

894
01:04:16,152 --> 01:04:18,586
Hey, Steve. Are you just getting here?

895
01:04:18,754 --> 01:04:20,984
No, I was just outside
talking to the doctor.

896
01:04:21,157 --> 01:04:23,557
You don't remember us
talking 10 minutes ago?

897
01:04:23,726 --> 01:04:25,557
- We talked?
- Yeah.

898
01:04:25,728 --> 01:04:27,889
Hey, my hard disk crashed.

899
01:04:30,766 --> 01:04:33,428
A computer guy with memory problems.

900
01:04:35,371 --> 01:04:37,271
Oh, man.

901
01:04:37,440 --> 01:04:40,637
It's the weirdest thing.
You know there's a part of your life there...

902
01:04:40,810 --> 01:04:42,778
...only you don't know about it.

903
01:04:42,945 --> 01:04:45,311
It makes you crazy.

904
01:04:59,729 --> 01:05:01,492
Hey.

905
01:05:02,665 --> 01:05:04,929
Hey!

906
01:05:07,036 --> 01:05:08,663
Paul.

907
01:05:08,838 --> 01:05:11,329
Simonyi, get Matthews.

908
01:05:11,507 --> 01:05:13,441
Ballmer, get in here.

909
01:05:16,412 --> 01:05:19,438
- What is it?
- This is seriously crummy.

910
01:05:19,615 --> 01:05:22,175
Apple's new computer, Lisa? We're dead.

911
01:05:22,351 --> 01:05:23,909
Oh, yeah, I've already seen one.

912
01:05:24,086 --> 01:05:26,350
The graphics and the operating system
they have...

913
01:05:26,522 --> 01:05:29,355
...they make what we're selling IBM
look a decade out-of-date.

914
01:05:29,525 --> 01:05:31,652
- I want it.
- What do you mean, you want it?

915
01:05:31,827 --> 01:05:37,163
- It's Apple's. We can't just go and steal it.
- You're not listening to me. I want it.

916
01:05:37,333 --> 01:05:43,829
<i>Final call for TWA flight 2684
to San Jose. Final call. </i>

917
01:05:45,041 --> 01:05:48,533
- Fifty bucks he misses the flight.
- You're on.

918
01:05:48,711 --> 01:05:50,679
It wouldn't hurt to buy a car radio, Bill.

919
01:05:50,846 --> 01:05:53,076
- I can't pick up the radio...
- One traffic report.

920
01:05:53,249 --> 01:05:55,740
- Hold on.
- Sir, we're on this plane.

921
01:05:55,918 --> 01:05:58,751
I'm sorry. Your plane is on the runway.

922
01:05:58,921 --> 01:06:00,980
Ma'am, what kind of service
is this today?

923
01:06:01,157 --> 01:06:05,093
I'm sorry, sir. There's nothing that can bring
that plane back to the gate.

924
01:06:05,261 --> 01:06:08,924
Yes, there is. Willpower. I'm going to will
that that plane be turned around.

925
01:06:09,098 --> 01:06:11,191
- Oh, really?
- Really, sir.

926
01:06:11,367 --> 01:06:15,167
Are you aware that today in my briefcase
are computer language codes?

927
01:06:15,338 --> 01:06:17,932
- Do you know what they do, sir?
- I'm afraid I don't.

928
01:06:18,107 --> 01:06:21,167
They protect against viruses.
You're aware of viruses, I presume?

929
01:06:21,344 --> 01:06:25,713
- Sir, I do go to doctors.
- No, sir, computer viruses.

930
01:06:25,881 --> 01:06:28,281
Oh, yeah, I just read an article
about those things.

931
01:06:28,451 --> 01:06:31,477
- They can wipe out a whole computer.
- A whole system of computers.

932
01:06:31,654 --> 01:06:34,851
Like the one behind your terminal there,
like the one in the plane...

933
01:06:35,024 --> 01:06:39,222
...like the one on all planes in the airlines,
like the one in the control tower, sir.

934
01:06:39,395 --> 01:06:42,694
I ask you, are you prepared
to take responsibility for your actions...

935
01:06:42,865 --> 01:06:45,891
...if I don't get this information
on that plane?

936
01:06:47,570 --> 01:06:51,939
Jeez, his reputation for inconveniencing
the rest of the world is intact.

937
01:06:52,108 --> 01:06:53,803
He actually missed a flight.

938
01:06:53,976 --> 01:06:57,742
<i>This is your captain speaking. We have
to return to the gate for a few minutes. </i>

939
01:06:57,913 --> 01:07:00,211
<i>Nothing critical. </i>

940
01:07:05,654 --> 01:07:10,523
<i>- Attention, please, flight... 
- Your tickets, please.</i>

941
01:07:10,693 --> 01:07:14,959
- You have the tickets, right?
- No, I gave them to you.

942
01:07:16,132 --> 01:07:18,464
Bill, in the car.

943
01:07:35,117 --> 01:07:38,280
Wow. These guys must be
50 times bigger than we are.

944
01:07:38,454 --> 01:07:41,446
Good artists copy. Great artists steal.

945
01:07:41,624 --> 01:07:45,116
- Oh, yeah? Who said that?
- Some artist. I think it was Van Gogh.

946
01:07:46,429 --> 01:07:49,296
Hey, check it out.

947
01:07:50,800 --> 01:07:55,794
Aye, matey. It wouldn't be time
to rape and pillage, would it?

948
01:08:03,879 --> 01:08:06,814
You sure it's okay
to let these Microsoft guys in here?

949
01:08:07,116 --> 01:08:10,051
We have culture. They don't.

950
01:08:10,386 --> 01:08:13,480
No taste. No original thinking.

951
01:08:14,123 --> 01:08:16,421
But they can be useful to us.

952
01:08:17,059 --> 01:08:19,823
Time for the dog and pony show.

953
01:08:28,871 --> 01:08:31,237
Welcome to Apple.

954
01:08:41,484 --> 01:08:43,179
Bill.

955
01:08:44,420 --> 01:08:46,320
Nice to see you. Thanks for coming.
Steve.

956
01:08:46,489 --> 01:08:49,390
- How you doing, Steve?
- Glad you're here. Paul. Hi, Steve Jobs.

957
01:08:49,558 --> 01:08:52,118
- Hi. Charles Simonyi.
- Come on in. Let me introduce you.

958
01:08:52,294 --> 01:08:54,888
This is Gilmore.
He's one of our top programmers.

959
01:08:55,431 --> 01:08:58,025
And he's a loyal man.
Well, to do this, you need loyalty.

960
01:08:58,901 --> 01:09:02,098
- Total loyalty. Isn't that right?
- That's the plan, Steve.

961
01:09:02,872 --> 01:09:07,309
This way. The Macintosh team.
It's more like a family.

962
01:09:07,476 --> 01:09:10,309
Everybody else is an outsider.

963
01:09:10,479 --> 01:09:13,676
- What's with the pirate stuff?
- What do I always tell you?

964
01:09:14,150 --> 01:09:16,209
Better to be a pirate than join the Navy.

965
01:09:16,385 --> 01:09:19,548
- You a pirate?
- Oh, yeah. Yeah, absolutely, Steve.

966
01:09:20,122 --> 01:09:21,885
I've been up for 52 hours straight.

967
01:09:23,526 --> 01:09:24,754
Loyalty.

968
01:09:33,469 --> 01:09:35,494
I'm gonna show you the future.

969
01:09:35,671 --> 01:09:39,300
It's top-secret. It's still about...

970
01:09:39,475 --> 01:09:42,273
...a year away from introduction.

971
01:09:42,778 --> 01:09:45,645
The ultimate, insanely great...

972
01:09:47,216 --> 01:09:49,411
...fusion of art and science.

973
01:09:51,020 --> 01:09:55,150
- It's called the Macintosh.
- This is definitely not the Lisa.

974
01:09:55,324 --> 01:09:57,554
That's a graphic user interface.

975
01:09:57,726 --> 01:10:01,457
I don't understand. How does a computer
handle the mouse-cursor display?

976
01:10:01,630 --> 01:10:03,621
Hardware's got nothing to do
with the mouse.

977
01:10:03,799 --> 01:10:06,097
- It's all in the software.
- Enough.

978
01:10:06,268 --> 01:10:08,463
Sorry, Steve.

979
01:10:08,871 --> 01:10:12,329
There's no point in torturing our guests...

980
01:10:12,841 --> 01:10:15,309
...with what they can't have.

981
01:10:23,485 --> 01:10:26,283
You're vulnerable in spreadsheets,
you know, Steve.

982
01:10:26,455 --> 01:10:28,719
We can help you.

983
01:10:30,559 --> 01:10:33,790
Ninety hours a week. Like the T-shirt?
I'm gonna give it to my people.

984
01:10:36,232 --> 01:10:38,894
Some of them work even more
than 90 hours a week.

985
01:10:39,068 --> 01:10:41,969
We have Multiplan running on
dozens of different platforms.

986
01:10:42,137 --> 01:10:44,298
No one can match us.

987
01:10:45,107 --> 01:10:47,473
You can't just have employees anymore.

988
01:10:47,643 --> 01:10:49,270
It's great.

989
01:10:50,246 --> 01:10:52,305
No, they gotta be into a crusade.

990
01:10:52,481 --> 01:10:58,181
It's like art, science, religion,
all rolled into one.

991
01:10:58,354 --> 01:11:02,415
We have multi-tool interface.
It can be redesigned for the Mac.

992
01:11:02,591 --> 01:11:06,254
Redesigned. Redesigned.

993
01:11:06,895 --> 01:11:09,090
We're artists here.

994
01:11:09,265 --> 01:11:11,893
A place where raw sand
comes in one end...

995
01:11:12,067 --> 01:11:16,197
...and goes out the other. Silicon art.

996
01:11:18,841 --> 01:11:23,039
You know, IBM, they're gonna want
all our stuff.

997
01:11:23,779 --> 01:11:25,178
IBM?

998
01:11:27,016 --> 01:11:30,144
IBM, they're history.

999
01:11:30,319 --> 01:11:35,757
I mean, they're 1950s, they're ice America,
a bloated enemy in a crumbling castle.

1000
01:11:35,924 --> 01:11:38,722
- And we're storming it.
- I know IBM is the enemy, Steve.

1001
01:11:38,894 --> 01:11:41,089
But we can help you.

1002
01:11:41,630 --> 01:11:43,564
You don't have to worry about IBM.

1003
01:11:44,300 --> 01:11:46,234
Yeah?

1004
01:11:46,402 --> 01:11:48,427
So why you even working with them?

1005
01:11:49,104 --> 01:11:51,766
I'd much rather work with you.

1006
01:12:01,684 --> 01:12:03,549
We're in.

1007
01:12:04,119 --> 01:12:06,280
- We're doing work for Apple.
- You're kidding me.

1008
01:12:06,455 --> 01:12:09,390
They're sending us three prototypes
of the computer we just saw.

1009
01:12:09,558 --> 01:12:11,048
- The Macintosh.
- For God sakes.

1010
01:12:11,226 --> 01:12:14,992
There's a pirate flag flying above our heads,
and he's giving us the crown jewel?

1011
01:12:15,164 --> 01:12:16,791
Who the hell's the pirate here?

1012
01:12:16,965 --> 01:12:19,297
He sees what he believes,
not the other way around.

1013
01:12:19,468 --> 01:12:21,265
We're not his worst problem.

1014
01:12:21,437 --> 01:12:24,201
If he's not careful,
he's gonna wreck the place.

1015
01:12:25,207 --> 01:12:27,437
- Macintosh! Macintosh!
- Macintosh rules!

1016
01:12:27,609 --> 01:12:30,544
- Apple II's the best!
- Mac's the best!

1017
01:12:30,713 --> 01:12:33,978
<i>Even when I got my memory back,
it was never the same for me. </i>

1018
01:12:34,149 --> 01:12:36,117
<i>I couldn't believe
how it had all changed. </i>

1019
01:12:36,285 --> 01:12:38,412
<i>Apple was tearing itself to pieces. </i>

1020
01:12:39,021 --> 01:12:41,581
<i>Steve had turned it into two camps:</i>

1021
01:12:41,757 --> 01:12:46,285
<i>His new Macintosh group
against everyone else in the company. </i>

1022
01:12:50,432 --> 01:12:53,128
Steve, what the hell is this?

1023
01:12:53,669 --> 01:12:57,469
It's like a family. Things get messy.

1024
01:12:57,873 --> 01:12:59,238
I don't understand this.

1025
01:12:59,408 --> 01:13:02,571
You got the Mac people
against the Apple II people?

1026
01:13:02,745 --> 01:13:04,838
- They're beating each other up.
- Amazing, huh?

1027
01:13:05,013 --> 01:13:08,449
People wanna be shaped, molded.

1028
01:13:08,617 --> 01:13:11,347
But if you asked any of them,
any of them, they'd deny it.

1029
01:13:11,954 --> 01:13:16,288
I don't wanna shape anybody, Steve.
This isn't fun anymore.

1030
01:13:16,458 --> 01:13:20,019
Maybe fun is just fragments of existence
with better packaging.

1031
01:13:21,930 --> 01:13:23,397
I don't make jokes anymore.

1032
01:13:23,565 --> 01:13:27,399
I told you a long time ago, I like jokes.

1033
01:13:27,569 --> 01:13:32,836
Steve! Goodbye. I'm quitting Apple.

1034
01:13:34,109 --> 01:13:38,978
- Well, that's a joke, right?
- No. I'm going back to college.

1035
01:13:39,148 --> 01:13:44,950
Woz. Hey, what are you doing?
I don't think it's such a good idea.

1036
01:13:45,120 --> 01:13:49,022
All I'm doing now is being a brake pedal
for you as you're heading for the wall.

1037
01:13:51,627 --> 01:13:53,857
Woz!

1038
01:14:23,325 --> 01:14:26,260
- I ask you for brilliance?
- Steve.

1039
01:14:26,428 --> 01:14:31,388
I've asked you for genius,
and you're giving me this?

1040
01:14:32,668 --> 01:14:34,602
Steve, please.

1041
01:14:44,847 --> 01:14:47,577
Oh, no, Steve, not again.

1042
01:14:47,749 --> 01:14:51,708
It's 3 a. m., okay? I don't have the energy
to defend an unfinished design.

1043
01:14:51,887 --> 01:14:55,414
That's because there's nothing to defend.

1044
01:14:55,591 --> 01:14:59,925
I want beauty, not incompetence.

1045
01:15:00,662 --> 01:15:02,721
Are you listening to me?

1046
01:15:03,465 --> 01:15:05,365
- Are you listening...?
- Yes, I'm listening!

1047
01:15:05,534 --> 01:15:07,627
I am so sick of your abusiveness.

1048
01:15:08,904 --> 01:15:11,998
That's all you know.
Tearing people down, throwing tantrums.

1049
01:15:12,174 --> 01:15:17,578
- You miserable son of a bitch.
- What are you doing? Come on, back off.

1050
01:15:31,927 --> 01:15:34,953
<i>I know we've been in a battle... </i>

1051
01:15:35,130 --> 01:15:38,657
...and like all battles,
we've had our casualties along the way.

1052
01:15:39,468 --> 01:15:41,163
But today's about celebrating.

1053
01:15:43,138 --> 01:15:44,662
The Macintosh.

1054
01:15:51,246 --> 01:15:53,214
It's time for a christening...

1055
01:15:55,050 --> 01:15:57,814
...of our little Macintosh.

1056
01:15:57,986 --> 01:15:59,886
Our baby.

1057
01:16:09,698 --> 01:16:12,394
- Congratulations.
- Congratulations.

1058
01:16:14,136 --> 01:16:16,969
Real artists ship.

1059
01:16:17,406 --> 01:16:20,898
In this company, in Apple,
in the entire business...

1060
01:16:21,076 --> 01:16:25,809
...we, you, the Macintosh team,
are the only true artists.

1061
01:16:25,981 --> 01:16:28,677
You can forget Apple, forget Lisa.

1062
01:16:28,850 --> 01:16:32,377
It's only us. The Macintosh team.

1063
01:16:32,554 --> 01:16:35,387
We have been chosen to seize history.

1064
01:16:36,792 --> 01:16:42,458
But first, carpe diem, seize the day.
It's your time to party, people.

1065
01:16:44,800 --> 01:16:46,791
Hey, John.

1066
01:16:47,469 --> 01:16:49,027
You hear what I heard in there?

1067
01:17:17,132 --> 01:17:21,034
- Hey, man, what'd you say about Steve?
- I'm sick of his crap.

1068
01:17:21,203 --> 01:17:23,068
- What'd you say, man?
- You heard me.

1069
01:17:23,238 --> 01:17:25,433
You wanna talk like that about Steve?

1070
01:17:25,607 --> 01:17:28,269
You wanna talk like that about the guy
who feeds you, man?

1071
01:17:28,443 --> 01:17:32,345
- The guy who feeds you?
- Come on. Break it up.

1072
01:17:32,514 --> 01:17:34,311
Come on.

1073
01:17:35,784 --> 01:17:38,218
- Hey, hey, guys.
- Somebody pull him off.

1074
01:17:38,654 --> 01:17:41,487
- Never like this at Pepsi-Cola.
- Knock it off.

1075
01:17:41,957 --> 01:17:44,755
You wanna sell sugar water
the rest of your life?

1076
01:17:58,140 --> 01:18:00,370
Steve, I'm worried.

1077
01:18:02,844 --> 01:18:04,277
Yeah?

1078
01:18:04,446 --> 01:18:07,142
Yeah, about what's happening.

1079
01:18:07,582 --> 01:18:12,212
All the, you know, "them versus us" stuff.
Macintosh versus Apple II.

1080
01:18:12,387 --> 01:18:15,845
You don't understand, John.
People need a cause.

1081
01:18:16,024 --> 01:18:19,391
We missed Vietnam. This is our Vietnam.

1082
01:18:20,629 --> 01:18:24,292
- It's tearing the company apart.
- Creation is messy.

1083
01:18:24,466 --> 01:18:27,264
You want genius, you get madness.
Two sides of the same coin.

1084
01:18:27,436 --> 01:18:29,529
You knew that when I brought you in.

1085
01:18:29,705 --> 01:18:32,265
Steve, if you can't trust me,
then God help you.

1086
01:18:32,441 --> 01:18:35,433
I didn't mention anything
about trust, John.

1087
01:18:39,081 --> 01:18:40,378
There's another problem.

1088
01:18:42,984 --> 01:18:45,544
- It's Arlene and the baby.
- That's my business.

1089
01:18:45,721 --> 01:18:49,782
<i>No, not anymore.
TIME magazine is doing another story.</i>

1090
01:18:49,958 --> 01:18:52,222
You don't need the bad press.
Neither do we.

1091
01:18:52,394 --> 01:18:55,329
- Child's not mine.
- Steve, come on. You took a paternity test.

1092
01:18:56,164 --> 01:18:58,598
She is yours.
It's right there in the results.

1093
01:18:58,767 --> 01:19:03,261
- Paternity tests are a joke.
- She's asking for $20,000.

1094
01:19:03,438 --> 01:19:05,838
- Total, nothing more.
- Blackmail.

1095
01:19:06,007 --> 01:19:08,976
Steve, you can afford the money.
Give her what she's asking for.

1096
01:19:09,144 --> 01:19:11,874
- You should give her more.
- It's not about the damn money.

1097
01:19:12,214 --> 01:19:14,409
Well, what is it, then?

1098
01:19:14,583 --> 01:19:16,676
I don't know.

1099
01:20:08,670 --> 01:20:11,400
Mommy, there's a man here.

1100
01:20:28,423 --> 01:20:31,620
It's been what, a year?

1101
01:20:34,629 --> 01:20:38,588
- Yeah, I've been busy.
- I'm sure.

1102
01:20:40,802 --> 01:20:44,704
- Why'd you come?
- I don't know.

1103
01:20:46,741 --> 01:20:48,641
She's looking really good.

1104
01:20:54,983 --> 01:20:57,383
You should have come to see her.

1105
01:20:57,552 --> 01:21:01,613
- You could have brought her by.
- Oh, Steve.

1106
01:21:04,326 --> 01:21:06,260
Here.

1107
01:21:16,471 --> 01:21:18,405
Thank you.

1108
01:21:19,007 --> 01:21:20,998
Thank you, Lisa.

1109
01:21:57,279 --> 01:22:00,680
- Steve Jobs is killing us. Ballmer!
- Yeah?

1110
01:22:00,849 --> 01:22:02,817
This stuff is crummy. It's totally crummy.

1111
01:22:02,984 --> 01:22:05,817
- Windows was supposed to ship last year.
- We're ready for you.

1112
01:22:05,987 --> 01:22:08,455
Why do I have to do this?
I have work. This is stupid.

1113
01:22:08,623 --> 01:22:10,750
<i>It's good PR.
It's for The Wall Street Journal.</i>

1114
01:22:10,926 --> 01:22:13,656
- I don't need PR.
- Can you stand a little to the left?

1115
01:22:13,828 --> 01:22:17,264
The hole in that sweater of your shirt.
Turn all the way to the right.

1116
01:22:17,432 --> 01:22:19,024
What am I, a trained seal?

1117
01:22:19,200 --> 01:22:22,363
- Lf Apple can do this, why can't we?
- What do you want us to do?

1118
01:22:22,537 --> 01:22:24,664
- Whatever you have to.
- Meaning what, Bill?

1119
01:22:24,839 --> 01:22:26,966
Meaning ship Windows
before the snow falls.

1120
01:22:27,142 --> 01:22:29,736
- This is Seattle. It doesn't snow here.
- Whatever, Steve.

1121
01:22:29,911 --> 01:22:32,379
Mr. Gates, I think you should
take off your sweater...

1122
01:22:32,547 --> 01:22:34,674
...because it clashes
with the background.

1123
01:22:34,849 --> 01:22:37,010
The green and blue,
it's just not in these days.

1124
01:22:37,185 --> 01:22:39,176
It's not in at all.

1125
01:22:39,354 --> 01:22:42,790
Sweat stains. This is awful.

1126
01:22:49,064 --> 01:22:52,397
- I'd like to get back to work...
- I know, we're almost ready.

1127
01:22:52,567 --> 01:22:58,870
Okay, and three, two, one.
Smile, please.

1128
01:22:59,741 --> 01:23:01,868
Urgent, Mr. Gates.

1129
01:23:02,043 --> 01:23:04,807
Thank you. What's next?

1130
01:23:06,247 --> 01:23:08,078
Steve Jobs.

1131
01:23:08,416 --> 01:23:11,180
"Mr. Jobs demands you be
in his office tonight. "

1132
01:23:12,854 --> 01:23:14,845
He's getting paranoid
over what we're doing.

1133
01:23:15,290 --> 01:23:16,621
Maybe he should be.

1134
01:23:17,892 --> 01:23:19,917
Not at the pace you're going.

1135
01:23:20,095 --> 01:23:22,086
I think I had a date tonight with Ann.

1136
01:23:22,263 --> 01:23:24,288
- I thought she was away on business.
- She is.

1137
01:23:24,466 --> 01:23:26,024
Then how can you have a date?

1138
01:23:26,201 --> 01:23:30,001
Well, I go to a movie here, and then
she goes to the same movie in Denver...

1139
01:23:30,171 --> 01:23:32,799
...and then we talk on the phone
about it afterwards.

1140
01:23:32,974 --> 01:23:37,138
Jeez, Bill, I hate to see what happens
when you two have sex.

1141
01:24:20,488 --> 01:24:23,480
You're stealing from us!

1142
01:24:26,127 --> 01:24:29,460
Steve, we're not stealing from you.
So don't tell me that.

1143
01:24:30,799 --> 01:24:32,460
What the hell are you doing, then?

1144
01:24:32,634 --> 01:24:37,094
What is this that I keep hearing
about you developing this...?

1145
01:24:37,272 --> 01:24:39,866
What do you call it? Windows?

1146
01:24:40,041 --> 01:24:42,373
To compete with us?

1147
01:24:44,946 --> 01:24:49,315
- I'm not doing anything against you, Steve.
- Don't give me that crap!

1148
01:24:49,484 --> 01:24:52,783
You're pirating the software
off our Mac prototypes!

1149
01:24:52,954 --> 01:24:54,615
I trusted you.

1150
01:24:55,190 --> 01:24:59,627
If you wanna know everything
we're working on, I'll show you.

1151
01:25:07,202 --> 01:25:08,567
<i>The weird thing was... </i>

1152
01:25:08,736 --> 01:25:12,433
<i>... Steve Jobs was the one guy
Bill would never yell at. It was the opposite. </i>

1153
01:25:12,607 --> 01:25:15,838
<i>Steve would order Bill to fly down there
and then blow up at him... </i>

1154
01:25:16,010 --> 01:25:19,707
<i>... but Bill, he would just wait it out,
convince Steve that we were no threat... </i>

1155
01:25:19,881 --> 01:25:23,476
<i>... that this Windows stuff was just
that much more smoke and mirrors... </i>

1156
01:25:23,651 --> 01:25:25,915
<i>... and a few hours later,
everything was fine. </i>

1157
01:25:26,087 --> 01:25:28,146
<i>I'm telling you, Bill's a genius at it. </i>

1158
01:25:29,424 --> 01:25:31,688
And that's all you're working on?

1159
01:25:32,160 --> 01:25:33,388
Of course.

1160
01:25:34,295 --> 01:25:36,593
- Yeah?
- You know what else?

1161
01:25:36,898 --> 01:25:40,493
Did you read what I said in that
newspaper story on us two days ago?

1162
01:25:40,935 --> 01:25:43,961
- No. What'd you say?
- I said when your Macintosh comes out...

1163
01:25:44,139 --> 01:25:47,006
...that'd be the only computer
I'd want to buy my mom.

1164
01:25:47,375 --> 01:25:49,605
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

1165
01:25:50,111 --> 01:25:52,671
Your mom, huh?

1166
01:25:52,847 --> 01:25:57,284
- It's like we're one big family, you know?
- Family?

1167
01:26:00,121 --> 01:26:01,349
You know that.

1168
01:26:05,727 --> 01:26:07,786
Family.

1169
01:26:09,364 --> 01:26:11,355
<i>Steve, Steve, Steve, Steve!</i>

1170
01:26:25,046 --> 01:26:26,570
Tell me something.

1171
01:26:26,748 --> 01:26:29,911
When did this stop being a business
and start being a religion?

1172
01:26:30,084 --> 01:26:31,483
Thank you for your work.

1173
01:26:31,653 --> 01:26:36,522
And remember, what we will do
in the next year...

1174
01:26:36,691 --> 01:26:39,717
...will change the way people think...

1175
01:26:39,894 --> 01:26:42,192
...and communicate.

1176
01:26:44,766 --> 01:26:46,597
Hey.

1177
01:26:46,768 --> 01:26:48,429
- Hey.
- So enjoy the revolution...

1178
01:26:48,603 --> 01:26:52,061
...which we have all created and watch...

1179
01:26:52,240 --> 01:26:54,105
You know, Steve thinks IBM's the enemy.

1180
01:26:54,275 --> 01:26:55,606
- Unfolds in front of us.

1181
01:26:55,777 --> 01:26:58,041
He doesn't get it.

1182
01:26:58,213 --> 01:26:59,908
You guys are.

1183
01:27:02,984 --> 01:27:05,043
What are you talking about?

1184
01:27:05,220 --> 01:27:07,950
Copies of your Windows
just started surfacing here.

1185
01:27:08,122 --> 01:27:09,612
You took our stuff, Bill.

1186
01:27:09,791 --> 01:27:13,192
You took our stuff, you fooled with it,
and you called it your own.

1187
01:27:15,430 --> 01:27:18,627
You always insult your guests like this?

1188
01:27:19,367 --> 01:27:21,528
Make no mistake.

1189
01:27:21,703 --> 01:27:25,503
We are all one big family.

1190
01:27:26,474 --> 01:27:29,602
And part of it
are our friends at Microsoft.

1191
01:27:34,249 --> 01:27:36,342
Bill?

1192
01:27:41,489 --> 01:27:43,957
Ladies and gentlemen, Bill Gates.

1193
01:27:48,296 --> 01:27:51,459
Finally, I wanna show you a preview...

1194
01:27:51,633 --> 01:27:55,296
...of the most amazing 60 seconds of film
you'll ever see.

1195
01:27:55,470 --> 01:27:57,700
And we're showing it only once...

1196
01:27:57,872 --> 01:27:59,362
...during the Super Bowl.

1197
01:27:59,540 --> 01:28:02,737
So watch and see how we handle IBM.

1198
01:28:03,244 --> 01:28:05,838
I mean Big Brother.

1199
01:28:08,316 --> 01:28:11,877
<i>See, that commercial was interesting
in a lot of ways... </i>

1200
01:28:12,053 --> 01:28:15,022
<i>... because when we're at
this big hoopla at Apple... </i>

1201
01:28:15,189 --> 01:28:18,920
<i>... and their engineers are unpacking
all these Japanese computers... </i>

1202
01:28:19,093 --> 01:28:21,618
<i>... with the first copies
of our stuff, Windows... </i>

1203
01:28:21,796 --> 01:28:25,061
<i>... that looks a lot like their stuff... </i>

1204
01:28:25,233 --> 01:28:27,224
<i>I mean, if I had to pick a moment... </i>

1205
01:28:37,278 --> 01:28:39,007
Hey...

1206
01:28:39,180 --> 01:28:41,842
...I'm getting
some pretty weird vibes here.

1207
01:28:42,016 --> 01:28:43,881
Sure we should stay around?

1208
01:28:44,652 --> 01:28:49,112
Sometimes you deal them.
Sometimes you fold them.

1209
01:28:50,858 --> 01:28:53,326
Now's not the time to fold.

1210
01:28:54,829 --> 01:28:58,390
<i>We shall prevail. </i>

1211
01:29:03,638 --> 01:29:06,573
I obviously made a mistake.

1212
01:29:09,143 --> 01:29:10,872
I made a mistake.

1213
01:29:12,280 --> 01:29:14,373
I trusted.

1214
01:29:15,316 --> 01:29:17,580
I believed.

1215
01:29:19,053 --> 01:29:21,317
Family.

1216
01:29:23,958 --> 01:29:27,621
Maybe a Mafia family.
You turn your back, and you get whacked.

1217
01:29:27,795 --> 01:29:32,129
Our guys come back from Japan
with this NEC...

1218
01:29:33,167 --> 01:29:37,729
...and it's loaded with Microsoft programs.
Your Microsoft programs.

1219
01:29:37,905 --> 01:29:40,567
They're almost identical to ours.

1220
01:29:43,745 --> 01:29:46,475
There may be some similarities, Steve.

1221
01:29:49,517 --> 01:29:51,178
Similarities?

1222
01:29:54,589 --> 01:29:56,955
Similarities?

1223
01:29:59,193 --> 01:30:02,094
- Try theft.
- Steve, all cars have steering wheels...

1224
01:30:02,263 --> 01:30:05,664
...but no one tries to claim
that the steering wheel was their invention.

1225
01:30:05,833 --> 01:30:09,929
- We have a contract, you and I.
- Well, you should read it more carefully.

1226
01:30:10,104 --> 01:30:11,935
What is this?

1227
01:30:12,407 --> 01:30:14,807
This is like doing business with...

1228
01:30:14,976 --> 01:30:16,238
...like, a praying mantis.

1229
01:30:16,411 --> 01:30:19,471
You get seduced
and then eaten alive afterwards.

1230
01:30:19,847 --> 01:30:21,974
Get real, will you?

1231
01:30:23,651 --> 01:30:27,849
You and I are both like guys
that have this rich neighbor...

1232
01:30:28,022 --> 01:30:30,115
...Xerox...

1233
01:30:30,291 --> 01:30:32,589
...that left the door open all the time.

1234
01:30:32,760 --> 01:30:35,627
And you go sneaking in
to steal the TV set.

1235
01:30:36,030 --> 01:30:40,330
Only when you get there,
you realize that I got there first.

1236
01:30:40,501 --> 01:30:42,867
I got the loot, Steve!

1237
01:30:43,638 --> 01:30:45,401
And you're yelling?

1238
01:30:45,573 --> 01:30:48,201
"That's not fair.

1239
01:30:48,376 --> 01:30:51,470
I wanted to try to steal it first. "

1240
01:30:57,118 --> 01:30:59,245
You're too late.

1241
01:31:05,726 --> 01:31:08,092
We're better than you are.

1242
01:31:12,800 --> 01:31:16,964
- We have better stuff.
- You don't get it, Steve.

1243
01:31:18,039 --> 01:31:20,633
That doesn't matter.

1244
01:31:38,993 --> 01:31:42,724
<i>You know, like a lot of things,
there always seems to be one last time. </i>

1245
01:31:42,897 --> 01:31:45,127
<i>For us, it was when we all
came together again... </i>

1246
01:31:45,299 --> 01:31:48,029
<i>... for this big party
Steve threw for his 30th birthday. </i>

1247
01:31:48,202 --> 01:31:50,227
<i>It was just one of those things. </i>

1248
01:31:50,404 --> 01:31:53,202
<i>You know, where you try really hard
to make something work... </i>

1249
01:31:53,374 --> 01:31:55,672
<i>... but somehow it just doesn't. </i>

1250
01:31:55,843 --> 01:31:58,971
<i>And maybe you should have known it
all along. </i>

1251
01:32:02,950 --> 01:32:06,477
- Is that really Ella Fitzgerald?
- I have absolutely no idea.

1252
01:32:09,757 --> 01:32:11,657
You hear the kind of food
they're serving?

1253
01:32:11,826 --> 01:32:14,420
- Salmon mousse, goat's cheese.
- I can't eat that stuff.

1254
01:32:14,595 --> 01:32:17,826
- Why don't we go to Denny's?
- Is that Joan Baez with him?

1255
01:32:17,999 --> 01:32:19,796
Wait, wait. Who's Joan Baez?

1256
01:32:21,035 --> 01:32:23,162
- Hi.
- John.

1257
01:32:29,610 --> 01:32:31,942
I need to talk to you. It's important.

1258
01:32:32,113 --> 01:32:34,411
Okay, John. Excuse me.

1259
01:32:39,487 --> 01:32:42,547
We've got a problem.
We've been asked to make a toast to Steve.

1260
01:32:42,723 --> 01:32:47,126
Me? Toast Steve? No way, man.
Not after what's happened. No way.

1261
01:32:47,295 --> 01:32:51,254
Oh, John, don't look at me. L...
Mike, you do it.

1262
01:32:51,432 --> 01:32:55,027
After the past few months?
I don't think so.

1263
01:32:55,636 --> 01:32:58,503
John, you're the one.

1264
01:32:58,673 --> 01:33:02,632
- No. Not now. Absolutely no way.
- Why not?

1265
01:33:03,010 --> 01:33:05,979
- Look, Steve thinks I'm his...
- He thinks you're what?

1266
01:33:16,257 --> 01:33:18,885
Ladies and gentlemen, a toast.

1267
01:33:19,193 --> 01:33:21,218
To a remarkable man.

1268
01:33:21,395 --> 01:33:23,226
A man who brought me
to this company...

1269
01:33:23,731 --> 01:33:26,962
...without whom none of this tonight
would ever have happened.

1270
01:33:27,134 --> 01:33:31,730
Steve Jobs, truly a guiding light.
A man who sees the future.

1271
01:33:31,906 --> 01:33:33,134
- Hear, hear!
- Steve.

1272
01:33:33,307 --> 01:33:34,604
Happy birthday!

1273
01:33:40,881 --> 01:33:44,339
It's weird, but sometimes you find things
that are more important to you...

1274
01:33:44,518 --> 01:33:48,352
...than the things you think are important.
You know what I mean?

1275
01:33:48,522 --> 01:33:51,355
Maybe it's just getting older.

1276
01:33:53,127 --> 01:33:57,325
Okay, guys. Let's see how we did.

1277
01:33:58,699 --> 01:33:59,927
That's a good one.

1278
01:34:11,812 --> 01:34:13,370
It's true.

1279
01:34:14,715 --> 01:34:18,708
We're learning about the size of the sun
versus the size of the Earth.

1280
01:34:31,032 --> 01:34:32,465
<i>Hi, Steve. </i>

1281
01:34:32,633 --> 01:34:36,399
<i>I think it's gonna be really interesting,
I mean, you and me together. </i>

1282
01:34:36,804 --> 01:34:38,635
Yeah.

1283
01:34:40,608 --> 01:34:42,599
It is.

